metadata.name: 7.356 degrees #95
metadata.description:
Start with something simple. Take four identical equilateral triangles and join them to form a pyramid. This is your building block – a regular tetrahedron, the simplest possible three-dimensional figure.

When you connect five such pyramids by attaching their faces, you will be left with a thin empty space between the first and last: a volumetric angle of 7.356 degrees. It’s too small to fit another piece and too big to be lost in numerical imprecision.

It is a surprising imperfection. You would expect a tetrahedron to behave similarly to its two-dimensional ancestor. When you arrange equilateral triangles, one next to the other like tiles, you can cover two-dimensional space without leaving an empty spot. You may go on forever, covering infinite planes and be sure that the six angles that meet at each point will add up to the perfect 360 degrees.

In three dimensions, it is not like this: you cannot use your building block to fully fill a void. It’s as if the mathematical rules –the ones we tend to idealise for elegance, harmony, and infallibility– broke when you raise complexity.

But mathematical beauty does not reside in perfection. It is through these exceptions that complexity emerges. So keep building, face by face, one block at a time, and embrace the surprising, chaotic aesthetics that appears. A different type of harmony – not based on impeccable proportions, but on unpredictability.

---

The colours of the structures are inspired by 16 paintings of Polish artists from the 19th and 20th centuries.

"In a window" by Anna Bilińska-Bohdanowicz
"Portrait of Jadwiga against a Yellow Background" by Józef Mehoffer
"Portrait of Zofia Okuń" by Edward Okuń

metadata.name: Florilegium #171
metadata.description:
Florilegium’s inspiration lies in the ancient art of botanical illustration.

Historically, a florilegium was an anthology of illustrations depicting exotic plants and creatures. These publications reached their peak in the 17th century, with notable examples such as Nehemiah Grew’s “Anatomy of Plants”, Ernst Haeckel’s “Kunstformen Der Natur” and Joseph Banks’ “Florilegium”. These publications have had a lasting impact on both science and art. Today, florilegia often document endangered plant species from specific locations or gardens and are among the most lavish and expensive of books to produce.

In this generative tribute to the ancient art of florilegia, imagined biomorphic forms compete for space in a garden based on the geometry of circles.

Generative artwork by AutoEclectus

Controls in live mode:
- After the reveal animation finishes, press [s] to save a png (4000 x 5000px)

metadata.name: Across Paper Stones #32
metadata.description:
Wherever you want to go, you'll find a path to take you there.

Each tile is made up of two deformed rectangles. One is drawn with a drifting, fragmented outline.

Over thirty color palettes are shuffled together on each output, helping form slight edges between groups.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: gimme all your love #129
metadata.description: Sometimes we feel so lost that we look for any way to find the ground beneath our feet again. Sometimes we try to feel something through other people, through looks, words, touches. This is a temporary cure, which sooner or later will stop helping.

metadata.name: citylines #150
metadata.description: For this project, I decided to learn how to code up isometric buildings using just lines, custome shapes, and fills. Pretty fun actually. In the process, some interesting distributions of buildings kept popping up - like buildings on the outer edges only for example. So I made them explicit features (City Splits). The variations you can expect are colors, city splits (trio is my favorite!), building pattern type (i love lines :)), max building height, and # of pyramids. I hope you get some amazing outputs! Enjoy :)

metadata.name: reborn #226
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Allégories booléennes #523
metadata.description:
"Allégories booléennes" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

This work is a continuation of research around the intersections of shapes that I have been exploring for a while. I wonder about the way in which they make it possible to bring out new compositions from superpositions of shapes that could initially represent a real disorder.

Controls:
• "a": Play the animation
• "s": Export the image (default 2160 × 3840px PNG)
• "h": Change export settings to high resolution (then press "s" to export a 6480 ×11520px PNG)
• "m": Change export settings to medium resolution (then press "s" to export a 4320 × 7680px PNG)
• "n": Back to 2160 × 3840px

Artwork by Julien Espagnon, 2022.

metadata.name: A Stroll through the Garden #228
metadata.description:
Exploring the medium, physical, digital, made with AI, is an endless and exciting walk through a garden full of discoveries and hidden corners.

The choice of linocut aesthetics is connected with the personal background as an artist who worked with graphic techniques, childhood memories and feelings of trees deprived of their leaves in winter.

Thanks to YulikolaY for getting the code ready for production.

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

January, 2023

metadata.name: The Wintertime #77
metadata.description:
"The Wintertime" is a collection of generative art that captures the essence of the winter season in a glitchy and abstract way. The pieces in this collection are a visual representation of the harshness and beauty of winter, where the cold and barren landscapes are juxtaposed against the sparkling snow and ice. The glitches and digital distortions in the art add a sense of chaos and unpredictability, mirroring the unpredictable nature of winter weather. The collection celebrates the winter season in all its raw and untamed glory. Each piece is unique and evocative, inviting the viewer to get lost in the beauty of the wintertime.

The work was inspired by the drip painting technique of Jackson Pollock and the minimalistic elegance of Japanese prints. Combining these two distinct styles creates a visually striking and thought-provoking collection that pays homage to the masters while pushing the boundaries of contemporary art.

This collection is the continuation of GPTree: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/17691

Genuary 2023: Recursive trees

metadata.name: Dopamine Dreams #187
metadata.description:
Dopamine is a chemical released in the brain that makes you feel good.

Dopamine Dreams is an exploration of using patterns and geometric forms to create something that also makes you feel good; to create something that feels natural, as if it has sprung from the ground or appeared in the sky.  

In this work, there is a conversation happening between two modes for drawing the same grid. One is tight, geometric and calm. The other is loose, loopy and excited. They overlap, interlace and compete to fill the space.  One cannot exist without the other. Balance is the the key. Between them they create a landscape in which to dream. 

Generative artwork by AutoEclectus

Controls in live mode:
- After animation stops, press [s] to save a png

@autoeclectus everywhere - Twitter, Instagram and Masterdon. 
https://autoeclectus.art

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #238
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

Made with Unity
